text: Dear Mr. Shyamalan, When I first saw unbreakable, I was fascinated and amazed by the kind of performance delivered by the cast (in 2014) Then came split. It was a normal day when I switched the Television on and decided to watch Split for the first time. I had completely fallen for James Mcavoy all over again after wanted and was completely blown by his performance.  As the movie ended, in the scene when David Dunne takes Elijah's name, Mr. Glass and the Unbreakable music started, I was filled with extreme joy and didn't take another second to guess that the Horde, Dunne and Glass belonged to the same universe.  Then, I dug deeper and found out that Split has a sequel and I just can't describe my reaction when i discovered that Glass releases on my birthday (18 January) I went completely gaga over it and am so, very delighted.  So, I wish the movie and everyone great luck knowing that it'll surely be a raging success.  From a fan and a fellow Indian.  Love, LALI.

text: This M. Night Shyamalan really pulled a big white rabbit out of the hat with "Split" - a great movie that turned utterly fantastic in the last few seconds with the reveal that it was a "sideways sequel" to "Unbreakable".  A lot of people felt let down by most of his movies since David Dunn and Elijah Price appeared on the screen.  What M. Night did was whet the appetites of a lot of the fans of his original movies. "Glass" is either going to be a feast or leave people with a bitter taste in their mouth. Based on these trailers, it looks more like feast. Barring some possibly negative reviews in the weeks before its released (I HOPE NOT), this movie could end up pulling in a record January box office.

text: While looking for the villains' hideout, David Dunn teams up with a now grown up Cole Sear who converses with the ghosts of the Beast's victims in order to covertly gain intel on the villains' whereabouts and plans. When they first meet, Cole initially mistakes him for a certain psychologist he once knew. During the climax, a dude with one buff arm saves David's life by staring down the Beast long enough for police SWAT teams to gun him down with snipers and assault rifles, because in this more realistic universe the police actually shoot and kill people. Elijah escapes with the help of some wolves made out of vines who carry him to an old fashioned village in the middle of a forrest where he's ultimately defeated by a blind girl who accidentally trips and knocks him over breaking his neck. Thus Mr. Glass is ironically defeated not by a superhuman with incredible abilities that he's so obsessed with, but instead by another person with a disability like himself. In the after credits scene, Mark Walberg cameos as a delusional man with a serious phobia of plants who spots one of the vine wolves and starts screaming, "It's happening again!"

text: Unbreakable was a good movie. But Split was way better. It was the best supervillain origins movie ever. The hole time you're there thinking that you are watching a horror movie. Then at the end comes the twist that it's just not a horror movie. It's the spinoff/sequel to Unbreakable. By watching both trailers for Glass you can anticipate it's going to be epic. Some people don't understand how awesome the cinematic universe for this movies is because they haven't watched one or any of the prequels. To enjoy this you have to watch both movies first "Unbreakable" and then "Split". The Horde is the sickest and most crazy supervillain ever. He is even cannibalistic. text: PLOT TWIST: I am calling it, the final battle between David and Kevin causes collateral damage when they both tap into their potential, throwing cars and debris at each others as well as punches and kicks which create minor level shockwaves, nothing like Man Of Steel but still dangerous if you are 50-70 feet distance to them. The girl from Split has mind/psionic powers and telekinesis she tries to contain the damage, then Glass watching from distance sees a kid on a wheelchair stuck among the wreck in the street. Glass starts shouting at Beast/Kevin to stop but the man is too far gone and as he throws David into a wall, bricks detach and begins to fall on the kid. Elahja propels as fast as he can on his wheelchair and saves the child shielding him. David emerges from the pile of bricks and concrete and sees the man dying with the kid in his arms and with his last breath he tells him: "I was wrong....Let go David....save them....I was wrong.....save them...."   Dunn is outmatched in speed, but in raw strength he has the edge, and he jumps onto the Beast and propels him throw walls like a battering ram then punches him into a an elecrical power turret. The short circuit causes a burst of electricity that fries Kevin's brain making his personalities loose control blending into each other until he fallls on his knees cathatonic.

text: The perfect movie to preview on May 9th as here at the McHenry, Illinois Library there is a copy of this movie available.  It's a hot pic so without knowing that I'll be back in two days I think I'll go ahead and add Glass to my wish list.  Of note is that Glass is more than your average movie.  It is actual a DNA particle accelerator for the 2019 King Jam conference.  Yeah Tomas and I are rendering Cyrus in 3-D so as to allow the spectrum of light to gather around the collider rings as we shoot ion spheres into a 360 degree and 3-D printed apparatus.  It's kinda cool these days when you can author notable ideas and hold them in your hand.  I call that a souvenir worth archiving.
